        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4035223818" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5494090103650331677">I listened to the audio of this book back in the 90s long before I was writing reviews for Goodreads.com. I was reminded of it by my &quot;1,000 Books to Read Before You Die&quot; calendar for May 31, 2021 which provides a short review that I&apos;ve copied below. The two things I remember most from the book was the 20th Maine’s bayonet charge and Longstreet&apos;s disagreements with Lee. I&apos;ve often wondered whether Longstreet&apos;s thoughts are based on any documented history. I suspect that they may be based on thing</span>
  <span id="freeText5494090103650331677" style="display:none">I listened to the audio of this book back in the 90s long before I was writing reviews for Goodreads.com. I was reminded of it by my "1,000 Books to Read Before You Die" calendar for May 31, 2021 which provides a short review that I've copied below. The two things I remember most from the book was the 20th Maine’s bayonet charge and Longstreet's disagreements with Lee. I've often wondered whether Longstreet's thoughts are based on any documented history. I suspect that they may be based on things Longstreet said after the war. <br /><br /><u>The following is from the calendar</u>:<br />In the fleet, fierce narrative of his Pulitzer Prize winning novel, <i>The Killer Angels,</i> Michael Shaara brilliantly shows "what it was like to <i>be</i>" at Gettysburg by recording the terrible butchery of the three days' fighting. Working from the combatants' own letters and other primary documents, Shaara has fashioned characters who live upon the page in a way that conveys the human drama of the epic battle that left 50,000 soldiers dead, wounded, or missing. The fears and hopes, memories and actions, of the protagonists in the face of Gettysburg's unrelenting carnage makes this one of the most deeply moving war novels ever written.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5494090103650331677" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
