    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_431708922" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/431708922" />
    <a title="Christopher Saunders" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13546014-christopher-saunders"><img alt="Christopher Saunders" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612565718p2/13546014.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/431708922?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christopher Saunders" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christopher Saunders" href="/user/show/13546014-christopher-saunders">Christopher Saunders</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13546014-christopher-saunders?shelf=2020-reads">2020-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13546014-christopher-saunders?shelf=pulitzer-prize-for-fiction">pulitzer-prize-for-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer431708922" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7898595491564016990">Michael Shaara&apos;s <b>The Killer Angels</b> offers an engrossing recreation of the Battle of Gettysburg. Shaara&apos;s narrative focuses primarily on four figures: Robert E. Lee, the Confederate General driven by hubris and bad luck (and, it&apos;s implied, ill health) to fight a battle he can&apos;t control; James Longstreet, his senior corps commander who recognizes the folly of launching an offensive battle against well-entrenched enemy troops; Union cavalryman John Buford, whose decision to engage Confederate infan</span>
  <span id="freeText7898595491564016990" style="display:none">Michael Shaara's <b>The Killer Angels</b> offers an engrossing recreation of the Battle of Gettysburg. Shaara's narrative focuses primarily on four figures: Robert E. Lee, the Confederate General driven by hubris and bad luck (and, it's implied, ill health) to fight a battle he can't control; James Longstreet, his senior corps commander who recognizes the folly of launching an offensive battle against well-entrenched enemy troops; Union cavalryman John Buford, whose decision to engage Confederate infantry on "good ground" initiates the battle; and Joshua Lawrence Chamberlain, the professor-colonel of the 20th Maine who plays a crucial role in the defense of Little Round Top. Shaara's book is a military narrative that largely elides the war's political background; there's some dated historiography in its treatment of certain characters and events (whether treating Lee's Army of Northern Virginia with a chivalrous deference that's hard to swallow, or repeating the myth that George Meade planned to retreat after the second day of battle). There's a lot of brother-against-brother sentimentalizing (particularly the chapters focusing on Confederate brigadier Lewis Armistead lamenting his friendship with Yankee corps commander Winfield Scott Hancock) which is either poignant or tiresome, depending on one's point of view. But these minor caveats are easily overcome by Shaara's vivid characterizations brilliant, his limpid, engrossing prose (an odd but engaging mixture of terse, clipped dialogue and sometimes-rambling internal monologues) and some of the best battle writing in modern literature. If Shaara isn't as politically perspicacious as some might like, he does use Longstreet, a cynic who predicts the disaster before it unfolds, to puncture Lost Cause mythology while Union motivations are largely debated by Chamberlain and his crusty Sergeant Buster Kilrain. In any case, it's still a moving, credible, deeply human portrait of men caught in a disastrous war, where luck, human frailties and split-second decisions from a few men can shape the fate of millions.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7898595491564016990" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


